      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Make the filling: melt 3 tablespoons of unsalted butter in a small bowl (microwave works well). Stir in 3 tablespoons granulated sugar, 2 tablespoons brown sugar, and 1 tablespoon ground cinnamon until a smooth, spreadable mixture forms. Set aside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Make the egg dip: whisk together the {{eggs}} and {{whole-milk}} of milk in a shallow bowl. Set aside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Make the coating: stir 2 tablespoons granulated sugar and 2 teaspoons ground cinnamon together in a small bowl. Set aside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Trim the crusts from each slice of {{bread}}. Using a rolling pin, roll each slice out to about 3 mm thickness. Spread a thin layer of the butter filling over each slice, then roll up tightly into a cylinder. Repeat for all 8 slices.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Melt 3 tablespoons of salted butter in a large frying pan over medium heat. Dip each roll-up in the egg mixture, then place seam side down in the pan. Fry in batches for 1 to 2 minutes per side until golden and slightly crisp on the outside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Remove to a board and sprinkle each roll-up generously with the cinnamon-sugar coating while still hot. Serve immediately with maple syrup.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Roll the bread more tightly before frying; press the seam down into the pan first to seal it with the heat.",
              "cause": "Roll not tight enough, or seam placed upward in the pan.",
              "symptom": "Roll-ups are unrolling in the pan"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Fry in batches of 3 or 4. Let the pan return to temperature between batches.",
              "cause": "Too many roll-ups in the pan at once, lowering the temperature.",
              "symptom": "Outside is pale and soft rather than golden"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use plain fresh soft sandwich bread, not sourdough or artisan loaves, which crack when rolled.",
              "cause": "Bread too thick or too firm.",
              "symptom": "Bread cracks when rolled"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Cream cheese filling: spread a thin layer of cream cheese before the cinnamon butter for a richer result.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Jam filling: skip the butter mixture and spread a teaspoon of jam before rolling.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Best eaten straight from the pan. The cinnamon-sugar coating softens as the rolls cool. Roll and fill ahead; fry just before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "French toast roll-ups are a modern North American variation on French toast. The method takes the logic of bread soaked in egg and fried in butter, and wraps it into a portable, finger-food format. Popular for brunch, family breakfasts, and occasions when you want something fun to eat with your hands.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
